title: For Sale:  Mauser K98
postcontent:
I have a Mauser K98, Mod 98, 8mm. This gun is still in cosmoline, basically new/old gun...I believe it is 1943, but not a mauser expert...But here is what I do know about it....

Yugo M-44 Mauser, 
This is NOT a Yugoslavian rifle, They BECAME Yugoslav rifles!!!

 What they actually are is GERMAN Kar98k rifles captured as the German army retreated and units surrendered at the end of WWII, the Yugo's arsenaled them, repaired them where necessary, buffed off the German markings on the receiver rings and stamped them with a Yugoslav crest instead and placed them in war reserve for over 60 years.  "Preduce 44" stamped on them to tell them apart from Yugoslavian produced Mausers, and shoot extremely well. They aren't really a Yugoslav Mauser, they are German Mauser wearing Yugoslav markings.

Also the marking on stock "1.TRZ"
Yugoslavian 1.TRZ
1 Tehnicki Remontni Zavod
 "1" stands for Cacak, Serbia
 "TRZ" translates to "technical repair facility"
 refurbishment mark
 Soviet M44 Stock

I am open to all offers..cash or trades welcome....I took this in on trade for cash owed to me and not my style of gun to keep....Please email or call or text my cell at 513-444-7778

title: For Sale:  .
For Sale/Trade:  1999 Tomos Targa LX
postcontent:
I have a 1999 Tomos Targa LX for sale. I bought it earlier this year with all intentions of adding performance parts to it and using it as a daily driver in nice weather, but since I have realized I really don't want to deal with all the work. That said it is a great moped.

 When I bought it, the original owner had just replaced the magneto and cleaned the fuel lines. Engine runs like a champ. All lights and horn work. The speedometer did not work so I removed it. Tires are also relatively new with only about 300 miles on them. The turn signals were a little bent up, but work fine. Also, the bracket on the seat could use a spot weld to hold it back in place. I can do that before the bike is sold.

 Since I have had it, I have driven it less than 60 miles. I removed the front wind screen and side covers because they were broken and repaired with the world's worst fiberglass job. I also replaced the original handlebars with a straight handlebar that gives the bike a little more aggressive look and more motorcycle like feel. I still have the original handlebars if they are desired. Unfortunately someone has knocked it over in the parking lot, which broke the tail light housing (light still works) and tore the grips. I have bought new grips for it and they will be installed before the bike is sold. I am listing these issues so you know I am honest and not trying to sell you a junker, because there are a lot of those out there. Other than those cosmetic issues, the moped is solid. The A-35 engine runs great and usually only takes one kick to start if it is run often. It will definitely hit 30-35 on a flat surface and more on a downward slope. The two-stroke oil is fed from a separate tank, so there is no mixing of fuel and oil to do. Gas tank is full and the oil is topped off. You can also have the rest of the oil. Also has valid plates, so you can drive it til they expire on Nov 9, 2014, then you will have to re-register it.

 Bought it just a few months ago in April for $550. Considering the work I did to it and damages to it, I would like about $500 for it, but price is negotiable. Email or text me at 4one2-4nine8-5zero4zero.  Also considering gun trades.  I'm looking for specific stuff, but let me know anything you have to trade

title: For Sale:  Glock 19 Gen 2 Austrian Import Proof Marked
postcontent:
For sale is a glock 19 gen 2 from 1989. This pistol has the austrian proof marks on the frame, barrel, and slide. All numbers matching. All original parts including black trigger parts and the uncaptured recoil spring and rod . Very rare. Comes with original mags. Very good condition considering the age. It has the old school finish, mill marks, and stamping/engraving. These are tested to 30% more pressure than the usa guns. 

Austrian proof marks means it was 100% made in austria. The "smyrna georgia" on the gun merely means it was imported. Thats an import mark. It does not say "made in..." All weapons for many decades have got to have an import stamp on them in order for them to be imported. That has nothing to do with where they are made. The proof marks prove where it was made. This is priced for as a collector for that glock collector. Dont be mad if you dont understand. If you want a new one for 500 go buy one this is not that. If you dont agree with me or whatever please respectfully move on.

I am a glock armorer so i do know what i am talking about.
